# Host Initialization & Config Override

## The problem

`initJerryLib()` without arguments calls `initAssets()` with no `overridePath`.
A3T then auto-initializes on first use using only the shipped defaults.
**User-local config files are silently ignored** unless the host explicitly passes `overridePath`.

## Required pattern for every host

Any host that installs `@sarkarshubhdeep/jerry-lib` from JSR **must** call
`initJerryLib` with `overridePath` before invoking `ask`, `generateReport`, or
`recheckReport`. Fail to do this and the user's `.config` overrides will never
be picked up, with no error or warning.

```ts
import { initJerryLib } from '@sarkarshubhdeep/jerry-lib'
import { join } from 'node:path'
import { homedir } from 'node:os'

// Call once at startup — before any ask/report call.
initJerryLib({
  assets: {
    overridePath: join(homedir(), '.config/<app-name>/assets'),
  },
})
```

Replace `<app-name>` with the host's own name (e.g. `jerry-cli`, `jerry-client`).

## Resolution order (once overridePath is set)

1. `~/.config/<app-name>/assets/<key>` — user override (highest priority)
2. Shipped `assets/` inside the JSR package — library defaults
3. Inline hardcoded fallback inside `getPrompt` calls — last resort

## What the override directory should contain

The override directory mirrors the shipped `assets/prompts/` layout:

```
~/.config/<app-name>/assets/
  prompts/
    report.txt   ← replaces shipped report prompt
    recheck.txt  ← replaces shipped recheck prompt
    ask.txt      ← replaces shipped ask prompt
```

Files that don't exist in the override directory fall through to shipped defaults automatically.

## Do not re-initialize

`initJerryLib` is guarded — calling it a second time without `assets` options is
a no-op. Always pass `assets.overridePath` on the **first** call (at app startup),
not conditionally later.
